# Personal Toolkit AWS

Personal Toolkit is a serverless personal dashboard built with AWS SAM, Amazon Cognito, API Gateway, Lambda, DynamoDB, S3, CloudFront, and vanilla JavaScript.

The application combines authenticated personal tasks, weather, international news, and local movie discovery in a single private dashboard. It is designed as a production-oriented portfolio project rather than a basic CRUD demo: authentication, per-user data isolation, infrastructure as code, and GitHub Actions CI/CD are all included.

## Highlights

- Secure sign-in with Amazon Cognito Hosted UI and OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code + PKCE.
- Per-user task isolation using Cognito `sub` claims and DynamoDB partition keys.
- Serverless backend with API Gateway HTTP API and a Python Lambda router.
- Static frontend deployed to S3 and served through CloudFront over HTTPS.
- External data integrations for RSS news, TMDB movies, and Open-Meteo weather.
- GitHub Actions CI/CD for tests, SAM validation, SAM build, backend deployment, frontend S3 sync, and CloudFront invalidation.

## Architecture

```text
Browser
  -> CloudFront
  -> S3 static frontend
  -> Cognito Hosted UI for authentication
  -> API Gateway HTTP API with JWT authorizer
  -> Lambda
       -> DynamoDB for user-scoped tasks
       -> RSS feeds for news
       -> TMDB for movie data

Browser also calls Open-Meteo and OpenStreetMap Nominatim directly for weather and location lookup.
```

See [ARCHITECTURE.md](ARCHITECTURE.md) for the full system design and deployment flow.

## Features

- Authentication: sign in, sign out, session restore, token refresh, PKCE callback handling.
- Tasks: create, complete, star, rename, delete, filter, and persist tasks per authenticated user.
- News: aggregate international RSS headlines with backend degradation handling and client-side RSS fallback.
- Movies: browse now-playing and upcoming movies by inferred local region through TMDB.
- Weather: search cities, use browser geolocation, view current weather and a 5-day forecast.
- UI: light/dark theme, responsive dashboard layout, reduced-motion support, and accessible controls.

## Repository Structure

```text
todo_aws/
├── frontend/                    Static SPA: HTML, CSS, JavaScript
├── backend/lambda_function.py    Python Lambda handler and route logic
├── infra/template.yaml           AWS SAM template
├── tests/                        Unit tests for auth and isolation behavior
├── .github/workflows/            CI/CD workflows
├── ARCHITECTURE.md               Architecture and deployment overview
├── APPLICATION_DOCUMENTATION.md  Detailed application documentation
└── archive/                      Historical design notes
```

## Local Checks

```bash
python3 -m unittest discover -s tests
python3 -m py_compile backend/lambda_function.py tests/test_lambda_auth.py tests/test_frontend_auth.py
node --check frontend/app.js
sam validate --template-file infra/template.yaml
sam build --template-file infra/template.yaml
```

## Local Frontend Preview

```bash
cd frontend
python3 -m http.server 8000
```

Then open:

```text
http://localhost:8000/
```

The SAM template keeps localhost callback URLs available for local Cognito testing.

## CI/CD

The project uses GitHub Actions:

- `CI`: runs Python unit tests, Python compile checks, frontend JavaScript syntax checks, `sam validate`, and `sam build`.
- `Deploy Backend`: manually deploys the AWS SAM backend stack with Cognito, API Gateway, Lambda, and DynamoDB.
- `Deploy Frontend`: manually syncs `frontend/` to S3 and invalidates the CloudFront distribution.

Required GitHub repository secrets:

```text
AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID
AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
TMDB_API_KEY        # optional for deployment, required for the movie feature
```

## Deployment Notes

After backend deployment, copy the SAM outputs into `frontend/config.js`:

```text
ApiUrl
AwsRegion
CognitoDomain
CognitoClientId
```

For deployed Cognito callback/logout URLs, use HTTPS CloudFront URLs. Cognito allows `http://` only for localhost development URLs.

## Portfolio Summary

This project demonstrates:

- Serverless AWS application design.
- Cognito-based authentication and JWT authorization.
- Secure multi-user data isolation.
- Infrastructure as code with AWS SAM.
- CI/CD with GitHub Actions.
- Static frontend deployment through S3 and CloudFront.
